items.title: Calling model_admin.get_queryset with test Request breaks plugins
items.body:
In utils.py, line 183, you create a fake request object, and pass this to model_admin.get_queryset() on line 186.

However, this ignores changes made to the request object in Django middleware. In particular, some plugins, such as Django-Guardian, require the request object to pass through the site middleware.

Django-Guardian, a row-level permissions app, expects to find the user attribute. Because you are passing it a fake Request object, the "user" attribute does not exist.

I fixed the problem by changing utils.get_model_queryset, adding an additional parameter: context, and retrieving the actual Request object from the context.

I then pass the context to utils.get_model_queryset in templatetages/jet_tags.jet_sibling_object_url()

However, there still seem to be issues with how the Guardian templates are interacting with the Jet templates that I have yet to resolve. In particular, CSRF is not passed reliably into the Guardian templates, and the User menu in the upper left is garbled.

This is a similar issue to that of #58 but in a different context. In `vendor.css` there are a number of background image paths, like so:

  background: url("../../../jquery-ui/themes/base/images/ui-bg_flat_75_ffffff_40x100.png") 50% 50% repeat-x #fff;

The actual path for that image relative to vendor should be `/jquery-ui/themes/base/images/ui-bg_flat_75_ffffff_40x100.png` from what I can tell. There are 13 instances of these bad paths in that file (covering all of the images in `/static/jet/css/jquery-ui/images/`) along with one in `_messages.scss` (that bad path is then in the compiled `base.css` for each theme ie `light-blue/base.css` but I did not touch those as I assumed they are updated before releases)

However they do crash [whitenoise](http://whitenoise.evans.io/en/stable/) (and possibly other) static serving methods which expect to be able to rewrite css paths. I get an error like so:

```
app_label = field.remote_field.model._meta.app_label
```
